rows.name: Apollo Control Sensor
rows.description:
This sensor is required for a vehicle to subscribe to the control topic of Apollo. This sensor also demonstrates how a user can check when SVL Simulator receives the first control message from the AD stack like Apollo. Based on this time, you can start the rest of the simulation or do some other interesting things.
See https://www.svlsimulator.com/docs/simulation-content/sensors-list/#apollo-control for more details.

rows.description:
This sensor will visualize bounding boxes on objects as detected by Apollo Stack. It does not publish any data and instead subscribes to a topic from Apollo perception module. The color of the boxes are:
	[
		"Car": "Green"
		"Pedestrian": "Yellow"
		"Bicycle": "Cyan"
		"Unknown":  "Magenta"
	]
See https://www.svlsimulator.com/docs/simulation-content/sensors-list/#apollo-perception-visualizer-3d for more details.

rows.name: CAN Bus Sensor
rows.description:
This sensor sends data about the vehicle chassis. The data includes:
	* Speed [m/s]
	* Throttle [%]
	* Braking [%]
	* Steering [+/- %]
	* Parking Brake Status [bool]
	* High Beam Status [bool]
	* Low Beam Status [bool]
	* Hazard Light Status [bool]
	* Fog Light Status [bool]
	* Left Turn Signal Status [bool]
	* Right Turn Signal Status [bool]
	* Wiper Status [bool]
	* Reverse Gear Status [bool]
	* Selected Gear [Int]
	* Engine Status [bool]
	* Engine RPM [RPM]
	* GPS Latitude [Latitude]
	* GPS Longitude [Longitude]
	* Altitude [m]
	* Orientation [3D Vector of Euler angles]
	* Velocity [3D Vector of m/s]
See https://www.svlsimulator.com/docs/simulation-content/sensors-list/#can-bus for more details.

rows.name: Lidar Sensor
rows.description:
This sensor returns a point cloud after 1 revolution.
See https://www.svlsimulator.com/docs/simulation-content/sensors-list/#lidar for more details.

rows.name: Signal Sensor
rows.description:
This sensor returns ground truth data for traffic light signals connected to the current lane of ego vehicle and creates bounding boxes around the detected signals. The color of the bounding box corresponds to the signal's type:
	[
		"Green": "Green"
		"Yellow": "Yellow"
		"Red": "Red"
	]
See https://www.svlsimulator.com/docs/simulation-content/sensors-list/#signal-sensor for more details.

rows.name: Segmentation Camera Sensor
rows.description:

	"InstanceSegmentationTags": [

		"Pedestrian",
		"Obstacle",
		"Building"
	]
See https://www.svlsimulator.com/docs/simulation-content/sensors-list/#segmentation-camera for more details.

rows.name: 2D Ground Truth Sensor
rows.description:
This sensor outputs an image where objects are encased in a box. The color of the box depends on the type of object.
	[
		"Car": "Green"
		"Pedestrian": "Yellow"
		"Bicycle": "Cyan"
		"Unknown":  "Magenta"
	]
See https://www.svlsimulator.com/docs/simulation-content/sensors-list/#2d-ground-truth for more details.

rows.name: 3D Ground Truth Sensor
rows.description:
This sensor returns 3D ground truth data for training and creates bounding boxes around the detected objects. The color of the object corresponds to the object's type:
	[
		"Car": "Green"
		"Pedestrian": "Yellow"

	]
See https://www.svlsimulator.com/docs/simulation-content/sensors-list/#3d-ground-truth for more details.

rows.name: Control Calibration Sensor

See https://www.svlsimulator.com/docs/simulation-content/sensors-list/#control-calibration for more details.

rows.name: Differential Drive Control Sensor
rows.description:
The **Differential Drive Control** plugin provides a means for driving differential drive robots (ego) vehicles. Differential drive is a drive mechanism commonly used in mobile robots where two wheels are mounted on a common axis and each is capable of being driven forward or backward independently.

Differential drive robots often have wheel encoders that precisely track the rotation of each wheel. The rotation of each wheel can be used both as feedback for a closed loop controller to precisely control the robot motion, and for dead reckoning.

For more details, check: <https://www.svlsimulator.com/docs/simulation-content/differential-drive-control>

rows.name: ROS2ForUnitySVLBridge
rows.description:
ROS2 For Unity svl bridge by Robotec.ai

If you are using this plugin with ADE image in Autoware.Auto (https://www.autoware.org/) project then you are good to go and don't need to do anything. Otherwise, you have to prepare your SVL simulator:

IMPORTANT #1: This bridge requires additional binaries based on your ROS2 and OS versions. Go to https://github.com/RobotecAI/ROS2ForUnity/releases to download required archive, then extract its contents to SVL simulator:
1. libraries from `Plugins/<OS_NAME>/x86_64/*` put into `simulator_Data/Plugins` of svl simulator directory,
2. libraries from `Plugins/*.dll` put into `simulator_Data/Managed` of svl simulator directory.

IMPORTANT #2: In order for plugin to work, you have to also set "LD_LIBRARY_PATH" points to " <APP>/simulator_Data/Plugins" folder.

IMPORTANT #3: You must have your ROS2 environment sourced before running application.

This is native ROS2 bridge implementation based on ros2-for-unity project: https://github.com/RobotecAI/ros2-for-unity

Source code: https://github.com/RobotecAI/ROS2ForUnity

rows.name: IMSF1Tenth
rows.description:
The **IMS F1Tenth** map is a 1/10th scale version of the [Indianapolis Motor Speedway](maps/profile/62765742-57bf-4ccd-85e5-db8295d34ead).

The Indianapolis Motor Speedway located in Speedway, IN, is home to the IndyCar Series, **NASCAR Cup Series**, and many more. The 2.5-mile oval constructed in 1909 features the top races in the world such as the **Indianapolis 500**, **Brickyard 400**. The Indianapolis Motor Speedway also hosts a 2.439-mile road course that features the INDYCAR Grand Prix.

This map is intended for use with [F1TENTH](https://f1tenth.org/) simulation and 1/10 scale vehicles such as the [F1TENTH Traxxis vehicle](/vehicles/profile/3bb4c2eb-82d3-4ee3-8ebb-2bdbcf6e88ea).

Check <https://www.indianapolismotorspeedway.com> for more details.

rows.name: LasVegasMotorSpeedway
rows.description:
Las Vegas Motor Speedway, located in Clark County, Nevada about 15 miles northeast of the Las Vegas Strip, is a 1,200-acre complex of multiple tracks for motorsports racing.

The 1.5-mile oval has hosted everything from NASCAR races, concerts and the Electric Daisy Carnival to the ReMax World Long Drive Championship and Red Bull Air Race World Championships through the years, and it is a facility like none other. The track features 20-degree banking in the turns and 9- to 12-degree straightaways, and NASCAR's elite can reach speeds nearing 200 miles per hour. LVMS has been known to create highly competitive races for decades and is a favorite among drivers.

Updated 11/17/2021: Rotated map and added additional spawn points for multi-ego simulations

The Red Bull Ring is located Spielberg, Styria, Austria and is hosting Formula 1, Formula 2, Moto Gp and DTM competitions. We also created a corresponding 2D dataset that includes the X- and Y-position of the inner and outer bounds of the racetrack which can be found here: 
https://github.com/f1tenth/f1tenth_racetracks/tree/main/Spielberg

This also include a raceline (X-and Y-waypoints) that can be followed to drive fast around the track.
